	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Jun 10th 11:04 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'll just use dazzle for the single target mez and mez for aoe mez for less confusion<br><br>AE mez isn't that great, but it is useful.&nbsp;&nbsp;Usually I won't use aoe mez unless there are problems-- i.e. an unexpected pull of 6 or so, or if 3 are on the cleric that needs to be free for heals immediately, (especially if the tank isn't a taunt class--hey we all have had those kind of groups where sometimes tanks&#8217; damage alone does not taunt well enough).   Or if there are problems targeting (which usually isn't that bad).  Usually in situation where there is a really bad pull or many mobs are hitting the wrong people, I will aoe mez, tash and dazzle any that resist (thank the gods for channeling and the quick cast time of tash! :)), then tash the remainder, to get them ready for future dazzling and aoe mezzing, If i have time and mana and is feasible(especially if i am worried about my health), i might even root one or two (so that when they break mez i have extra time to remez/dazzle them with out them bashing on me.)  <br>If there is an insane number of guys around, but the tanks and cleric could be able to handle them all if they get them one by one, I will continue the aoe mez, (possibly root) and dazzle any singles I can, possibly ones that have been rooted far off  :)  , over and over until they are all dazzled.<br>If you know from experience that these are very high magic resist mobs, you could try workign with your tanks' taunt or root if necessary to tash first then start the aoe mez cycle<br><br>And although there should be time when you see a big pull to back away in preparation for ae mez so you don't mez yourself, if you do mez yourself, one mob might resist and attack you immediately, or it might wear off and they'll come after you<br><br>Don't forget if they are on you the cleric is open for heal.  Sometimes I might chain aoe mez and tash individuals if there are way way too many, and we are preparing for an evac.  Although yah you the chanter does haste and debuff, the primary and most important role of the chanter is crowd control.   <br><br>bottom line it is a matter of taste and style, but I do not use this style w/ aoe mez regularly---I use aoe mez for huge pulls or times when one of your members is very close to dying and has several on them--where there isn't enough time to taunt them all off or single mez them all off, so, basically, emergencies.  <br><br>oh! one more emergency hehe if the chanter is low on mana for some strange reason (maybe more applicable to lower levels) then aoe mez saves mana so the group can run to zone etc if it is plausible) Of course every case is different and must be evaluated case to case, but i have had a pretty good success rate for these general tactics in emergencies above :)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
